  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Every year in April, Brisbane's property market runs into a cluster of public holidays that affects how buyers behave, how marketing performs, and how contracts move. Easter (Good Friday, Easter Saturday, Easter Sunday, Easter Monday) is followed within one to three weeks by Anzac Day on April 25. Together these holidays produce a period of two to three weeks in which the working rhythm of buyer enquiry, open home attendance, and conveyancing throughput is disrupted. Sellers who plan around this window get cleaner campaign data, better attendance at open homes, and contracts that move on time. Sellers who do not plan around it can find themselves running the most expensive weeks of their campaign through a stretch when the market is half asleep.</p>

      <p>This article walks through how the April holiday cluster affects different parts of a typical Brisbane sale campaign, when to launch around it, when to pause, and what to expect from buyer behaviour through the period. The thinking applies to both auction and private treaty campaigns, with some additional notes on auction-specific timing.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The shape of the April public holiday cluster</h2>
      <p>Easter moves around the calendar each year, falling somewhere between late March and late April. In years where Easter is late, it can land within a week of Anzac Day, producing an effectively continuous holiday window of two and a half weeks where most of Brisbane is in school holidays, on leave, or running on a partial week. In years where Easter is early, the gap between Easter Monday and Anzac Day can stretch out, giving buyers and sellers a clearer working week or two between the two events. Either pattern still produces meaningful disruption: the school holidays around Easter alone change which families are in town, which families are away, which buyers are attending open homes, and which solicitors and conveyancers are running on reduced capacity.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Buyer behaviour through Easter</h2>
      <p>The week leading into Easter is typically a strong week for online enquiry but a weaker week for open home attendance. Buyers research properties on portals while away on holidays or while preparing for the long weekend, but physical attendance at Saturday opens in the days immediately before Easter is reliably down. The Easter long weekend itself is, for most properties, a write-off in attendance terms. The week after Easter, particularly if it coincides with school holidays continuing, sees a measured but not full recovery in physical attendance as families return progressively from coastal trips, interstate travel, and time off. The full recovery in attendance and enquiry typically arrives in the first full working week clear of both Easter and Anzac Day.</p>

      <p>Buyers in serious purchase mode (those at the inspection, finance, and contract stage on a specific property) generally continue to engage through the Easter and Anzac period, but more slowly. Solicitors, conveyancers, mortgage brokers, banks, and building and pest inspectors all run on reduced capacity through the holiday cluster. Contracts that would normally take five business days to finance-condition can stretch to seven or eight, and contracts that are already on a tight timeline can find themselves under pressure for extensions.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Launching a campaign before, during, or after the holiday cluster</h2>
      <p>For most Brisbane sellers, the cleanest launch position is either two to three weeks before Easter (allowing the first two weekends of the campaign to run before the holiday cluster compresses attendance) or in the first full clear week after Anzac Day (allowing the campaign to launch into a recovered market). Launching directly into Easter week itself produces a campaign that opens with low enquiry, low attendance, and weak signal: buyers cannot tell whether the property is genuinely soft or just running through a quiet window, and sellers cannot tell either. This makes pricing decisions and any conversation about market feedback harder to ground in real data.</p>

      <p>The pre-Easter launch works best for properties where the marketing story is strong enough to capture serious buyer interest in the first two weekends. The post-Anzac launch works best for properties that benefit from the broader rhythm of the autumn market, with a clear runway through May into the early winter selling window. Both options are usually preferable to launching through the holiday cluster itself.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Pausing or continuing an existing campaign</h2>
      <p>For properties that are already on the market when the Easter and Anzac period arrives, the question is whether to maintain the open home schedule through the holiday cluster or pause for one to two weeks. The case for continuing is straightforward: serious buyers are still active, the cost of the open homes themselves is small, and missing a serious buyer who happened to be free on the Saturday before Easter is more damaging than running a quiet open home. The case for pausing is that low-attendance opens produce weak signal, can read poorly on the campaign report (six or seven attendees on a Saturday that would normally produce twenty in a strong campaign tells the wrong story), and pull the agent's energy through a window where buyer engagement is harder to convert.</p>

      <p>The right answer is usually a hybrid. Maintain visibility online through the holiday cluster (the listing stays active, enquiries are responded to promptly, private inspections continue for serious buyers), but consider scaling back the public open home schedule for the most disrupted weekend (typically the Easter Saturday open). The agent's read of the buyer pipeline at that point matters more than a general rule. If there are three active families at the inspection or finance stage, continuing the public opens has lower marginal benefit than focused private inspections with those buyers. If the campaign is in early-week attendance mode and casting a wider net, a low-key open home through the holiday cluster keeps the listing visible.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Auction campaign timing around the holidays</h2>
      <p>Auction campaigns in Brisbane typically run on a four-week cycle, with the auction date set at the end of that period. For auction campaigns, the Easter and Anzac cluster has a more pronounced effect because the auction date itself either falls in or near the holiday window. Setting an auction date for the Easter Saturday is rarely a good decision; attendance and bidder registration tend to be lower than a comparable weekend on either side. Setting an auction for the Saturday between Easter and Anzac Day is usually fine in years where the calendar gives a clear Saturday between the two events, but tighter in years where the calendar compresses the gap. Most experienced agents will move auction dates forward or back a week to land on a clean Saturday with normal attendance.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Settlement timing and the conveyancing pipeline</h2>
      <p>Sellers should also think about the settlement implications of contracts signed in the lead-up to Easter and Anzac Day. A 30 or 45 day settlement set on a contract that goes unconditional in late March can land directly in the holiday cluster, where the conveyancing pipeline (PEXA platform, mortgage discharge, council and water rates clearance, settlement attendance) is running on partial staffing. Settlement extensions during the April holiday period are not unusual and not necessarily a sign of buyer or seller stress, but they do require agent and conveyancer coordination. Sellers planning to coordinate the sale with a simultaneous purchase should be particularly careful with settlement dates that fall in the Easter to Anzac window, because a one or two day delay on either side can cascade into bridging finance or accommodation issues.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Marketing spend and digital exposure</h2>
      <p>Online portal enquiry, while lower in attendance terms, often holds up reasonably well through Easter as buyers research properties on holiday or in downtime. This means the marketing spend on portal premium listings, social media, and email campaigns continues to generate value through the holiday cluster, even though the conversion to physical attendance lags. Sellers and agents should think about this as a delayed-conversion period rather than a dead window: the buyer who sees the listing on their phone over Easter weekend may attend the open home in the first weekend after the cluster ends, having already done the research. Continuing the digital marketing through Easter is usually worth the spend; pulling the open home schedule for one weekend is sometimes the right call.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">School holiday families and interstate buyers</h2>
      <p>The Queensland school holidays around Easter affect family buyer behaviour in two opposing directions. On one hand, families on holidays in Noosa or the Sunshine Coast are not at Brisbane open homes. On the other hand, families on holidays in Brisbane (particularly interstate families using the holiday window for a relocation reconnaissance) are sometimes the most active buyer cohort of the entire month. Sellers in suburbs that attract Sydney and Melbourne relocators (Bulimba, Hawthorne, Norman Park, parts of Camp Hill, parts of Coorparoo at the higher price points) sometimes see strong inspection activity from interstate buyers during the Easter school holidays specifically because those buyers are using the holidays to compress their property search into a one-week trip. This is a small but meaningful segment for inner-east family homes in the right price band.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">A practical timing checklist for sellers</h2>
      <p>For sellers planning a campaign around the Easter and Anzac period, the practical checklist is roughly as follows. Identify the dates of Easter and Anzac Day for the relevant year and map out the affected weekends. Decide whether the cleaner launch is two to three weeks before Easter or in the first full clear week after Anzac Day. If launching pre-Easter, plan the campaign rhythm so the first two opens fall before the holiday cluster compresses attendance. If launching post-Anzac, use the lead time to complete preparation (styling, photography, marketing copy) so the launch into the recovered market is sharp. Avoid setting an auction date on Easter Saturday or Anzac Day. Build settlement timelines that allow for the conveyancing pipeline running on partial capacity through the holiday cluster. And throughout, work with an agent who has run several campaigns through April in your suburb and knows what attendance patterns and contract timelines look like through the disruption.</p>

